{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/are-you-still-using-sklearn-for-regression-analysis-fb06bb06ce96", "time": 1683008058.5443468, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/are-you-still-using-sklearn-for-regression-analysis-fb06bb06ce96/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Are you still using sklearn for Regression Analysis? | by Roman Orac | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Are you still using sklearn for Regression Analysis?", "description": "For most Data Scientists sklearn is the first go-to package when it comes to classical Machine Learning algorithms in Python. But that doesn\u2019t mean there aren\u2019t other great packages available for\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://twitter.com/robinhanson/status/803302419249725440?lang=en", "anchor_text": "Robin Hanson", "paragraph_index": 3}, {"url": "http://statsmodels", "anchor_text": "statsmodels", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_linear_model", "anchor_text": "1", "paragraph_index": 7}, {"url": "https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LinearRegression.html", "anchor_text": "LinearRegression", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression.html", "anchor_text": "LogisticRegression", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://scikit-learn.org/dev/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.PoissonRegressor.html#sklearn.linear_model.PoissonRegressor", "anchor_text": "PoissonRegressor", "paragraph_index": 14}, {"url": "https://twitter.com/romanorac", "anchor_text": "Twitter", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "https://twitter.com/romanorac/status/1328952374447267843", "anchor_text": "tweet", "paragraph_index": 18}], "all_paragraphs": ["For most Data Scientists sklearn is the first go-to package when it comes to classical Machine Learning algorithms in Python. But that doesn\u2019t mean there aren\u2019t other great packages available for modeling. The package I am presenting in this article is mostly related to regression analysis, which many Data Scientists unjustifiably relate to simplistic modeling.", "Here are a few links that might interest you:", "Some of the links above are affiliate links and if you go through them to make a purchase I\u2019ll earn a commission. Keep in mind that I link courses because of their quality and not because of the commission I receive from your purchases.", "Most firms that think they want advanced AI/ML really just need linear regression on cleaned-up data. Robin Hanson tweet.", "While I feel the sarcasm in the tweet above, mastering the main assumptions of Linear Regression is far from simplistic (eg. multicollinearity, multivariate normality, homoscedasticity, etc.). Another thing that many Data Scientists don\u2019t know is that Linear Regression and Logistic Regression are part of the same family of algorithms \u2014 Generalised Linear Models (GLM).", "I always liked how R gives you a detailed output after training a regression model. A Python package that provides a similar output is statsmodels \u2014 a package for the estimation of many different statistical models, as well as for conducting statistical tests and statistical data exploration.", "In the image below, we can observe a summary of a regression model trained with statsmodels. It looks similar to the one in R. It even displays warnings, which is another advantage over sklearn.", "As already mentioned above, Logistic and Linear Regression are part of a bigger family called Generalized Linear Models. The GLM generalizes linear regression by allowing the linear model to be related to the response variable via a link function and by allowing the magnitude of the variance of each measurement to be a function of its predicted value. Generalized linear models were formulated by John Nelder and Robert Wedderburn as a way of unifying various other statistical models, including linear regression, logistic regression and Poisson regression [1].", "To learn more about GLM, listen to a great Andrew Ng\u2019s Lecture:", "GLM lets you use probability distributions as building blocks for modeling. Let\u2019s look at an example of Logistic Regression with statsmodels:", "In the example above, Logistic Regression is defined with a binomial probability distribution and Logit link function. Note, y_train is an array with target variable and x_train represents an array of features.", "Intercept column (a column of 1s) is not added by default in statsmodels. We can add it with:", "To use Linear Regression (Ordinary Least Squares Regression) instead of Logistic Regression, we only need to change family distribution:", "Another commonly used regression is Poisson regression, which assumes the target variable has a Poisson distribution. It is used to model variables that are counts, like the number of colds contracted in schools. Again, with statsmodels, we only need to change family distribution:", "While there are LinearRegression, LogisticRegression and PoissonRegressor in sklearn, I really like how statsmodels API is implemented. It also offers many customizations, which I am going to touch in my next article about statsmodels.", "One of the downsides of using statsmodels over sklearn is that it doesn\u2019t have support for sparse matrices. This makes it infeasible to train the model with many sparse features, like textual features transformed with a bag of words approach.", "The sklearn documentation is superior to statsmodels documentation.", "Overall sklearn seems more optimized in comparison with statsmodels.", "Follow me on Twitter, where I regularly tweet about Data Science and Machine Learning.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ffb06bb06ce96&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------